.TH "Element.clientTop" "JS" "July 26, 2024" "JavaScript" "JavaScript Reference Manual"
.SH NAME
Element.clientTop \- Element: clientTop property
.SH SYNOPSIS
The width of the top border of an element in pixels.
It is a read\-only, integer property of element.
.PP
As it happens, all that lies between the two locations
(\f[CR]offsetTop\f[R] and client area top) is the element\[cq]s border.
This is because the \f[CR]offsetTop\f[R] indicates the location of the
top of the border (not the margin) while the client area starts
immediately below the border, (client area includes padding.)
Therefore, the \f[B]clientTop\f[R] value will always equal the integer
portion of the \f[CR].getComputedStyle()\f[R] value for
\[lq]border\-top\-width\[rq].
(Actually might be Math.round(parseFloat()).)
For example, if the computed \[lq]border\-top\-width\[rq] is zero, then
\f[B]\f[CB]clientTop\f[B]\f[R] is also zero.
.RS
.PP
\f[B]Note:\f[R] This property will round the value to an integer.
If you need a fractional value, use
\f[CR]element.getBoundingClientRect()\f[R].
.RE
.SH VALUE
A number.
.SH EXAMPLES
In the following example, the client area has a white background and a
24px black \f[CR]border\-top\f[R].
The \f[CR]clientTop\f[R] value is the distance from where the margin
(yellow) area ends and the padding and content areas (white) begin: that
is, 24px.
